    {
      "id": "99ac78aa29a3e821d2ebcd9daebb8fe42bef6988",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 529,
        "name": "Ben Evans",
        "email": "beevans@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bevans"
      },
      "date": "2018-10-30 18:09:11.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1\n\nWouldn't it make more sense to repeatedly call the ioctl with a maximum number of lines?  llog_print is in the warning/debug section of lctl, so even if it is slow, it's not critical-path.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "2b4e9c30d1a5f9f4376776f7e35f12db56b81659",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2018-10-30 19:32:58.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1\n\n> Wouldn't it make more sense to repeatedly call the ioctl with a\n > maximum number of lines?  llog_print is in the warning/debug\n > section of lctl, so even if it is slow, it's not critical-path.\n\nSure, but it restarts the llog printing from the beginning each time.  We'd have to change the interface to allow it to continue from where it left off.  Probably the easiest would be to do it one record at a time, so that each line was always guaranteed to fit into the buffer, but it would need more changes both to lctl and the kernel.\n\nThat said, the current approach isn't as simple as I thought it would be, and is failing when the buffer size is large, so I need to debug it more.\n\nIf you want to look at the \"return one line per ioctl()\" or YAML-formatted debugfs file approach in parallel that would be great.  We want the simplest fix possible for 2.12 so that it might still have a chance to be included into the release, and  larger improvements should be targeted for 2.13.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "a8cb5b37eba22a642f9fd7a9f13d4dc76b33d63c",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2018-11-20 22:24:43.000000000",
      "message": "Abandoned\n\nAbandon this approach.  It turns out that llog_print already has a mechanism to specify start/end records, so that should be used instead.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    }
  ],
